history.content:
I think that's nothing to fear, I know multiple folks who have FAILED the class (some subset of those people took the class again the next semester). All of these folks are now graduated, working in software, and still able-bodied humans.

After starting work, I sometimes wish I was more experienced with Linux, particularly with fancy terminal commands. It's definitely not needed, but I would feel cooler. I considered taking 9E, but dropped it, and instead told myself I would "learn the things on my own, without the pressure of a grade!" What ended up happening was I self-learned some things, and am avid about looking up bash-things, but have still never written even a small project in bash. Something about the feel of the college meta made me only see things all the way through if it was a class I was taking.

Up to you! Some say it's boring, but maybe you'll feel cool being able to do 16 seconds of repetitive work in 8 seconds of fancy thinking work. Just my opinion, nothing wrong with trying it out and dropping it later (hopefully you'll at least feel guilted into learning tidbits here and there).

I'm taking CS9E, a self paced computer science class this semester.

The class is one semester long, but their is an option where you can receive an incomplete for the first semester you take it and then complete the work the next semester and get a grade.

How would this look on my transcript?

Would the incomplete be erased once I complete the work?

I don't want an incomplete marking on my transcript :(

Thanks!
history.subject: Receiving an Incomplete grade in a self-paced CS class
